{{nihongo|'''Taga-taisha'''|多賀大社}} is a [[Shinto]] [[Jinja (Shinto)|shrine]] located in [[Taga, Shiga|Taga]], [[Shiga Prefecture]], [[Japan]] dedicated to [[Izanagi]] and [[Izanami]]. It is associated with long life, successful marriage and good fortune. The shrine is frequently referred to as {{nihongo|O-taga-san|お多賀さん}} by local residents. The gardens of the inner ''[[shoin]]'' are a [[Cultural Properties of Japan|nationally-designated]] [[Monuments of Japan|Place of Scenic Beauty]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bunka.go.jp/bsys/maindetails.asp?register_id=401&item_id=1575 |title=多賀神社奥書院庭園 |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref>

==History==
This ancient shrine is old to have been mentioned in the ''[[Kojiki]]''. According to that text it dates from 620, having been built during a time when [[Buddhism]] and Shinto were both doing very well. It contains both a Buddhist temple and Shinto shrine. The shrine has beautiful garden and a stone bridge, which were constructed by [[Toyotomi Hideyoshi]] as an offering for his mother's long life. It is next to the study attached to the Shrine offices.

==Festivals==
*{{nihongo|'''Korei-taisai'''|古例大祭}}: Most important festival held on April 23. Also known as {{nihongo|'''Taga-matsuri'''|多賀まつり}}.
*{{nihongo|'''Otaue-sai'''|御田植祭}}: A festival of planting rice with traditional rites held on June 7.
*{{nihongo|'''Mantō-sai'''|万灯祭}}: A lantern festival held on the night of August 3-5.

==Specialty goods==
*{{nihongo|'''Otaga-shakushi'''|お多賀杓子}}: A talisman shakushi (Japanese [[Ladle (spoon)|ladle]]) from the reign of [[Empress Genshō]]. Allegedly the origin of the Japanese word ''[[tadpole|otamajakushi]]''.
*{{nihongo|'''Itokiri-mochi'''|糸切餅}}: A ''[[wagashi|Japanese sweet]]'' made of [[mochi]] rice sold at souvenir shops around the shrine. Itokiri-mochi was first made to celebrate the [[Mongol invasions of Japan|Japanese victory over the Mongols]].{{Citation needed|date=November 2009}}

==Access==
About 20 minutes walk from [[Taga Taisha-mae Station]] on the [[Ohmi Railway]] [[Ohmi Railway Taga Line|Taga Line]], or about 10 minutes by bus from [[Minami-Hikone Station]] on the [[West Japan Railway Company|JR West]] [[Biwako Line]].

